Completeness and cardinality statements can be extended with information on their temporal validity. Darari et al. [darari2018completeness], for instance, introduced the notion of time-stamped completeness statements. These add a ``latest validity'' date to a completeness statement (which is typically, but not necessarily, the date of their creation). Examples are statements like ``Nobel Prize winners are complete until 2023'', or ``XYZ's publications are complete until 2018''.
Similarly, Arnaout et al. [ARNAOUT2021100661] extended negative statements inference with a notion of temporal prefix, allowing to conclude, for instance, that unlike her 7 predecessors, the German chancellor Angela Merkel was not male.